title: For Sale:  M1 Carbine - Plainfield Machine
postcontent: Collector-level quality and scarcity - the famed M1 Carbine !  From one of the best, most-boutique producers to ever tool up their machinery for these rifles!These rifles were made to be utilized as supporting infantry weapons and for arming support troops -- troops who might not be front-line infantry troops therefore not needing to carry the standard infantry battle rifle weapon, the M1 Garand and the much bigger .30-06 cartridge, or troops who carried other primary weapons/weapons systems (Mortar tubes or machine gun crews, as seen clearly in most episodes of The Pacific, as the M1 Carbine was widely fielded in the jungles of the Pacific Theatre of Operations in WWII) -- this gave them a lighter, shorter, easier to carry in hands, easier to sling on the body, and easier to fire and fire accurately -- but a weapon that still had much more firepower than the .45 ACP cartridge which had been (and was used widely, definitely) the caliber that armed support troops and secondary weapons - in the M1911 pistol and Thomspon sub-machine gun.  While .45 ACP is a significant pistol round, equipping war-fighting troops in enemy territory solely with a 7-shot pistol (.45 ACP or any caliber) was a recipe for disaster... and while the Thompson had great effect to 50 yards, the .45 ACP round gains absolutely little to no effect from carbine-length barrels, so using a Thomspon as an infantry weapon at any range greater than 50 yards is basically the same as using the M1911.  Therefore, the M1 Carbine was designed with a purpose-built, .30 Caliber round that was much better for war-fighting wih a 18" barrel than the pistol/submachine gun it was built to augment, and support troops and weapons crews /officers/etc. were widely issued the new-favorite weapon of the war, the M1 Carbine.  (There was later models, the M2 Carbine, which added fully-automatic fire, and an M3 Carbine, which added the first generation of nightvision called the "sniperscope"  -- it was like the original "car phones"-- a suitcase on top of a rifle) It was made by the famed "Plainfield Machine Co. Inc." of Dunellen, NJ (just so happens I'm in Dunnellon, FL now, no relation) -- this became the same company as the world-famous Iver Johnson company, which produced the absolutely-most-sought-after M1 Carbines (and M1911 pistols) on the market.  Before and after the merger and aquisition, and in the post WWII civilian market, Plainfield Machine Co. was a boutique M1 Carbine producer that used Plainfield-locally-made and machined receivers and barrels, with all other parts being USGI.  This rifle is highly sought after and in excellent condition -- but don't think it's only a showpiece, it's also an excellent "ranch rifle" or survival implement, or just truck gun to carry around in case you need it.The story with this particular rifle is as follows:  When my father became a police officer in the early 1970s, he was issued a service weapon but most of "the guys" would go to buy their own "off-duty" weapons and home-defense/"property guns" for around the ranch/yard/etc.  At some point in his earliest career, "the guys" were all going to the downtown K-Mart (yes, K-Mart sold guns back then) because someone knew someone who knew someone who knew that K-Mart just got a shipment of a small-batch of hand-crafted, locally-made rifles that everyone had to have.  Before moving down here a few years back, he even had the box it came in, with a K-Mart price tag sticker still stuck on the box (which got destroyed or lost in moving).  So my father went with the guys, bought the rifle everyone else was buying, and figured if nothing else it was a good deal on a great gun.He believes he has fired it two times, once immediately after purchasing it, and once about 20 years later when I was a little kid and wanted to "shoot the rifle".  This was probably 20 years ago.  It was then cleaned up and sent into storage and stayed there until moving down here a few years back.  Since then it's been in my safe.I have absolutely no use for this firearm as my desires lie elsewhere and my calibers and platforms are different.  Also, while I appreciate the fact my father owned it, we have actual family heirloom firearms and I'll own my father's actual service weapons and personal guns some day, this is not one of them, it's simply a rifle he bought.  Therefore I'd like to sell it to someone who'll appreciate it and I'll just get something more to my desires or with more utility for my needs and current platforms/portfolio of firearms and calibers.Other than the fact it was made in the early 1970s and so is therefore ~40+- years old, it's great and in great condition.  My father is not even sure a full box of 20 rounds of ammo was fired down the pipe, if it was it certainly has an extremely low round count, probably the lowest you could ever find.  He is not a "gun-guy" and as a cop he carried pistols, so this wasn't something he shot for fun or sport or work etc.  You can take advantage.Doing my research, I've seen Iver Johnson models go for several thousands of dollars, mint-condition and unfired Plainfield Machine Dunellen models go for $1000+ , and this is an excellent condition Plainfield Machine Dunellen model - the best and fairest median price I can relate it to is from $750-$1000.  I am going to go on the low end in the hopes the buyer will be someone who keeps it in their family a long time as well.  Thanks, hope to hear from you.Note: I was forced to select "Iver Johnson Arms" as the manufacturer on Armslist due to the fact they do not have a listing for "Plainfield Machine Co. Inc." but it is in fact a Plainfield-marked rifle with the mark clearly showing Plainfield, Dunellen NJ .30 Carbine  Last Note: My camera on my phone takes terrible indoor pictures, so the pictures suck, but don't fault the rifle, it's the phone.First person to email me saying they have cash in hand to buy gets it
